SIMPLE: shin
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shin
<hw>Shin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shine</ets>,
<ets>schine</ets>, AS. scina; akin to D. <ets>scheen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>scina</ets>, G. <ets>schiene</ets>, <ets>schien</ets>bein, Dan.
<ets>skinne</ets>been, Sw. <ets>sken</ets>ben. Cf.
<er>Chine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The front part of the leg below
the knee; the front edge of the shin bone; the lower part of the leg;
the shank.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧On his <xex>shin</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Railbroad)</fld> <def>A fish plate for rails.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shin bone</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the
tibia.</cd> -- <col><b>Shin leaf</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
perennial ericaceous herb (<spn>Pyrola elliptica</spn>) with a cluster
of radical leaves and a raceme of greenish white flowers.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shin
<hw>Shin</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shinned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shinning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To climb a mast,
tree, rope, or the like, by embracing it alternately with the arms and
legs, without help of steps, spurs, or the like; -- used with
<xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>shin</ex> up a mast</as>.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <-- now usu. shinny -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To run about borrowing money hastily and
temporarily, as for the payment of one's notes at the bank.</def>
<mark>[Slang, U.S.]</mark> <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shin
<hw>Shin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To climb (a pole, etc.) by shinning
up.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shindle</ent>⟦br⟧
